<BOS> Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation (or the Gates Foundation, abbreviated as BMGF) is the largest private foundation in the world <EOS>
<BOS> The foundation, based in Seattle, Washington <EOS>
<BOS> Warren Buffett (then the world's richest person, estimated worth of US$62 billion as of April 16, 2008) <EOS>
<BOS> pledged to give the foundation approximately 10 million Berkshire Hathaway Class B shares <EOS>
<BOS> In July 2013, Buffet announced another donation of his company's Class B, this time in the amount worth $2 billion <EOS>
<BOS> In November 2014, the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation announced that they are adopting an open access (OA) policy for publications and data <EOS>
<BOS> open access (OA) policy for publications and data, "to enable the unrestricted access and reuse of all peer-reviewed published research funded by the foundation <EOS>
<BOS> As of January 1, 2015 their Open Access policy is effective for all new agreements. <EOS>
<BOS> trustees divided the organization into two entities: the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation (foundation) and the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation Trust <EOS>
<BOS> The foundation section, based in Seattle, US, "focuses on improving health and alleviating extreme poverty <EOS>
<BOS> The trust section manages "the investment assets and transfer proceeds to the foundation as necessary to achieve the foundation's charitable goals <EOS>
<BOS> it holds the assets of Bill and Melinda Gates, who are the sole trustees, and receives contributions from Buffett <EOS>
<BOS> The foundation trust invests undistributed assets <EOS>
<BOS> exclusive goal of maximizing the return on investment <EOS>
<BOS> its investments include companies that have been criticized for worsening poverty in the same developing countries <EOS>
<BOS> These include companies that pollute heavily and pharmaceutical companies that do not sell into the developing world <EOS>
<BOS> the foundation announced in 2007 a review of its investments to assess social responsibility. It subsequently cancelled the review <EOS>
<BOS> n March 2006, the foundation announced a US$5 million grant for the International Justice Mission (IJM) <EOS>
<BOS> a human rights organization based in Washington, D.C., US to work in the area of sex trafficking. <EOS>
<BOS> the grant would allow the IJM to "create a replicable model for combating sex trafficking and slavery <EOS>
<BOS> conducting undercover investigations, training law enforcement, rescuing victims, ensuring appropriate aftercare, and seeking perpetrator accountability". <EOS>
<BOS> The IJM used the grant money to found "Project Lantern <EOS>
<BOS> "Project Lantern" and established an office in the Philippines city of Cebu. <EOS>
<BOS> IJM stated that Project Lantern had led to "an increase in law enforcement activity in sex trafficking cases <EOS>
<BOS> increase in services – like shelter, counseling and career training – provided to trafficking survivors" <EOS>
<BOS> the IJM was exploring opportunities to replicate the model in other regions. <EOS>
<BOS> The Water, Sanitation and Hygiene (WSH) program of the Gates Foundation was launched in mid-2005 <EOS>
<BOS> and became a full-fledged program under the Global Development Division in early 2010 <EOS>
<BOS> since 2005 undertaken a wide range of efforts in the WASH sector involving research, experimentation, reflection, advocacy, and field implementation <EOS>
<BOS> In 2009, the Foundation decided to refocus its WASH effort mainly on sustainable sanitation services for the poor, using non-piped sanitation services <EOS>
<BOS> This was because the sanitation sector was generally receiving less attention from other donors and from governments <EOS>
<BOS> In mid 2011, the Foundation announced in its new "Water, Sanitation, Hygiene Strategy Overview" <EOS>
<BOS> funding now focuses primarily on sanitation, particularly in sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia, because access to improved sanitation is lowest in those regions <EOS>
<BOS> Their grant-making focus has been since 2011 on sanitation science and technology ("transformative technologies") <EOS>
<BOS> delivery models at scale, urban sanitation markets, building demand for sanitation, measurement and evaluation as well as policy, advocacy and communications <EOS>
<BOS> Improved sanitation in the developing world is a global need <EOS>
<BOS> Improved sanitation in the developing world is a global need, but a neglected priority as shown by the data collected <EOS>
<BOS> About one billion people have no sanitation facility whatsoever and continue to defecate in gutters, behind bushes or in open water bodies <EOS>
<BOS> India is the country with the highest number of people practicing open defecation: around 600 million people <EOS>
<BOS> "Reinvent the Toilet Fair" in Delhi, India in March 2014. <EOS>
<BOS> In 2011, the foundation launched a program called "Reinvent the Toilet Challenge <EOS>
<BOS> to promote the development of innovations in toilet design to benefit the 2.5 billion people that do not have access to safe and effective sanitation <EOS>
<BOS> It was complemented by a program called "Grand Challenges Explorations" (2011 to 2013 with some follow-up grants reaching until 2015) <EOS>
<BOS> Both funding schemes explicitly excluded project ideas that relied on centralized sewerage systems or are not compatible with development country contexts <EOS>
<BOS> universities in the U.S., Europe, India, China and South Africa, have received grants to develop innovative on-site and off-site waste treatment solutions <EOS>
<BOS> The grants were in the order of 400,000 USD for their first phase, followed by typically 1-3 million USD for their second phase <EOS>
<BOS> many of them investigated resource recovery or processing technologies for excreta or fecal sludge. <EOS>
<BOS> The Reinvent the Toilet Challenge is a long-term research and development effort to develop a hygienic, stand-alone toilet <EOS>
<BOS> This challenge is being complemented by another investment program to develop new technologies for improved pit latrine emptying <EOS>
<BOS> The aim of the "Omni Processor" is to convert excreta (for example fecal sludge) into beneficial products such as energy and soil nutrients <EOS>
<BOS> The foundation has donated billions of dollars to help sufferers of AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria <EOS>
<BOS> protecting millions of children from death at the hands of preventable diseases <EOS>
<BOS> Gates grantees have increased the demand for specially trained, higher-paid clinicians, diverting staff from basic care" in sub-Saharan Africa <EOS>
<BOS> "the focus on a few diseases has shortchanged basic needs such as nutrition and transportation <EOS>
<BOS> discourage patients from discussing – ailments that the vaccinations cannot prevent". <EOS>
<BOS> has decided not to fund abortion" <EOS>
<BOS> the emotional and personal debate about abortion is threatening to get in the way of the lifesaving consensus regarding basic family planning <EOS>
<BOS> Up to 2013, the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation provided $71 million to Planned Parenthood <EOS>
<BOS> U.S. Libraries initiative with a goal of "ensuring that if you can get to a public library, you can reach the internet <EOS>
<BOS> Only 35% of the world's population has access to the Internet <EOS>
<BOS> The foundation has given grants, installed computers and software, and provided training and technical support in partnership with public libraries nationwide <EOS>
<BOS> this foundation helps move public libraries into the digital age. <EOS>
<BOS> A key aspect of the Gates Foundation's U.S. efforts involves an overhaul of the country's education policies at both the K-12 and college levels <EOS>
<BOS> including support for teacher evaluations and charter schools and opposition to seniority-based layoffs <EOS>
<BOS> It spent $373 million on education in 2009. <EOS>
<BOS> The foundation was the biggest early backer of the Common Core State Standards Initiative. <EOS>
<BOS> One of the foundation's goals is to lower poverty by increasing the number of college graduates in the United States <EOS>
<BOS> One of the ways the foundation has sought to increase the number of college graduates is to get them through college faster <EOS>
<BOS> Reimagining Aid Design and Delivery" grants to think tanks and advocacy organizations <EOS>
<BOS> As part of its education-related initiatives, the foundation has funded journalists, think tanks, lobbying organizations and governments <EOS>
<BOS> Millions of dollars of grants to news organizations have funded reporting on education and higher education <EOS>
<BOS> critics have feared the foundation for directing the conversation on education or pushing its point of view through news coverage <EOS>
<BOS> the foundation has said it lists all its grants publicly <EOS>
<BOS> Teach Plus, which was founded by new teachers and advocates against seniority-based layoffs <EOS>
<BOS> they may marginalize researchers who do not support Gates' predetermined policy preferences <EOS>
<BOS> Several Gates-backed policies such as small schools, charter schools, and increasing class sizes <EOS>
<BOS> but some studies indicate they have not improved educational outcomes and may have caused harm <EOS>
<BOS> Peer reviewed scientific studies at Stanford find that Charter Schools do not systematically improve student performance <EOS>
<BOS> the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation Trust, which manages the endowment assets and the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation <EOS>
<BOS> spend all of [the Trust's] resources within 20 years after Bill's and Melinda's deaths <EOS>
<BOS> the proceeds from the Berkshire Hathaway shares he still owns at death are to be used for philanthropic purposes within 10 years <EOS>

<BOS> 1930s through much of the 1960s, Florida was essentially a one-party state dominated by white conservative Democrats <EOS>
<BOS> Florida residents have received more federal monies than they pay in taxes: the state is a net beneficiary <EOS>
<BOS> Since the 1970s, the conservative white majority of voters in the state has largely shifted from the Democratic to the Republican Party <EOS>
<BOS> continued to support Republican presidential candidates through the 20th century, except in 1976 and 1996, when the Democratic nominee was from the South <EOS>
<BOS> the luxury of voting for presidential candidates who pledge to cut taxes and halt the expansion of government <EOS>
<BOS> William C. Cramer in 1954 from Pinellas County <EOS>
<BOS> Cramer built a different Republican Party in Florida, attracting local white conservatives and transplants from northern and midwestern states <EOS>
<BOS> 966 Claude R. Kirk, Jr. was elected as the first post-Reconstruction Republican governor, in an upset election <EOS>
<BOS> 968 Edward J. Gurney, also a white conservative, was elected as the state's first post-reconstruction Republican US Senator <EOS>
<BOS> 1970 Democrats took the governorship and the open US Senate seat, and maintained dominance for years <EOS>
<BOS> In 1998, Democratic voters dominated areas of the state with a high percentage of racial minorities and transplanted white liberals <EOS>
<BOS> white liberals from the northeastern United States, known colloquially as "snowbirds <EOS>
<BOS> racial minorities and white liberals. Because of this, the area has consistently voted as one of the most Democratic areas of the state <EOS>
<BOS> Republicans, made up mostly of white conservatives, have dominated throughout much of the rest of Florida <EOS>
<BOS> Daytona Beach, Orlando, and Tampa/St. Petersburg, has had a fairly even breakdown of Republican and Democratic voters <EOS>
<BOS> The area is often seen as a merging point of the conservative northern portion of the state and the liberal southern portion <EOS>
<BOS> the voting results in this area, containing 40% of Florida voters, has often determined who will win the state of Florida in presidential elections <EOS>
<BOS> Reapportionment following the 2010 United States Census gave the state two more seats in the House of Representatives <EOS>
<BOS> The legislature's redistricting, announced in 2012, was quickly challenged in court, on the grounds that it had unfairly benefited Republican interests <EOS>
<BOS> Florida Supreme Court ruled on appeal that the congressional districts had to be redrawn because of the legislature's violation of the Fair District Amendments <EOS>
<BOS> it accepted a new map in early December 2015. <EOS>
<BOS> Out of more than 5.8 million votes for the two main contenders Bush and Al Gore, around 500 votes separated the two candidates <EOS>
<BOS> Florida's felony disenfranchisement law is more severe than most European nations or other American states <EOS>
<BOS> if the state’s 827,000 disenfranchised felons had voted at the same rate as other Floridians, Democratic candidate Al Gore would have won Florida <EOS>
<BOS> that at least two districts had to be redrawn because of gerrymandering <EOS>
<BOS> lawmakers had followed an illegal and unconstitutional process overly influenced by party operatives, and ruled that at least eight districts had to be redrawn <EOS>
<BOS> a 5-2 majority of the Court accepted a new map of congressional districts <EOS>
<BOS> There are likely to be additional challenges to the map and districts. <EOS>

<BOS> were general services, financial services, trade, transportation and public utilities, manufacturing and construction respectively <EOS>

<BOS> Somerset is a rural county of rolling hills <EOS>
<BOS> Blackdown Hills, Mendip Hills, Quantock Hills and Exmoor National Park, and large flat expanses of land including the Somerset Levels <EOS>
<BOS> There is evidence of human occupation from Paleolithic times, and of subsequent settlement in the Roman and Anglo-Saxon periods <EOS>
<BOS> a significant part in the consolidation of power and rise of King Alfred the Great, and later in the English Civil War and the Monmouth Rebellion <EOS>
<BOS> substantial Georgian architecture and is a UNESCO World Heritage Site <EOS>
<BOS> Anglo-Saxon Chronicle's entry for AD 845 <EOS>
<BOS> The archaic name Somersetshire was mentioned in the Chronicle's entry for 878 <EOS>
<BOS> it went out of fashion in the late 19th century <EOS>
<BOS> As with other counties not ending in "shire," the suffix was superfluous, as there was no need to differentiate between the county and a town <EOS>
<BOS> Britain was invaded by Anglo-Saxon peoples <EOS>
<BOS> by the early eighth century King Ine of Wessex had pushed the boundaries of the West Saxon kingdom far enough west to include Somerset <EOS>
<BOS> was used several times in the 10th century to host the Witenagemot <EOS>
<BOS> HM Prison Shepton Mallet, which was England's oldest prison still in use prior to its closure in 2013, having opened in 1610 <EOS>
<BOS> Monmouth Rebellion was played out in Somerset and neighbouring Dorset <EOS>
<BOS> The Industrial Revolution in the Midlands and Northern England spelled the end for most of Somerset's cottage industries <EOS>
<BOS> Farming continued to flourish <EOS>
<BOS> Coal mining was an important industry in north Somerset <EOS>
<BOS> iron ore in the late 19th century; this was taken by the West Somerset Mineral Railway to Watchet Harbour for shipment to the furnaces at Ebbw Vale <EOS>
<BOS> Many Somerset soldiers died during the First World War, with the Somerset Light Infantry suffering nearly 5,000 casualties <EOS>
<BOS> only nine, described as the Thankful Villages, had none of their residents killed <EOS>
<BOS> for troops preparing for the D-Day landings <EOS>
<BOS> The Taunton Stop Line was set up to repel a potential German invasion <EOS>
<BOS> decoy towns were constructed in Somerset in World War II to protect Bristol and other towns, at night <EOS>
<BOS> mimic the geometry of "blacked out" streets, railway lines, and Bristol Temple Meads railway station, to encourage bombers away from these targets <EOS>
<BOS> Shepperton Studios, based on aerial photographs of the city's railway marshalling yards. The decoys were fitted with dim red lights <EOS>
<BOS> The Chew Magna decoy town was hit by half-a-dozen bombs on 2 December 1940, and over a thousand incendiaries on 3 January 1941 <EOS>
<BOS> are largely unaltered from medieval times <EOS>
<BOS> The River Avon formed much of the border with Gloucestershire, except that the hundred of Bath Forum <EOS>
<BOS> Edward III proclaimed "that the town of Bristol with its suburbs and precincts shall henceforth be separate from the counties of Gloucester and Somerset <EOS>
<BOS> in the late thirteenth century, but it declined in importance and the status of county town transferred to Taunton about 1366 <EOS>
<BOS> The county has two cities, Bath and Wells, and 30 towns <EOS>
<BOS> in terms of population are Bath, Weston-super-Mare, Taunton, Yeovil and Bridgwater <EOS>
<BOS> strategic importance in relation to geographical features, such as river crossings or valleys in ranges of hills <EOS>
<BOS> Chard is the most southerly town in Somerset, and at an altitude of 121 m (397 ft) it is also the highest <EOS>
<BOS> the Mendip Hills are moderately high limestone hills <EOS>
<BOS> Quantock Hills which was England's first Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty designated in 1956 <EOS>
<BOS> The Somerset Coalfield is part of a larger coalfield which stretches into Gloucestershire <EOS>
<BOS> on the clay substrate, are broad valleys which support dairy farming and drain into the Somerset Levels. <EOS>
<BOS> an extensive network of caves, including Wookey Hole <EOS>
<BOS> and gorges, including the Cheddar Gorge and Ebbor Gorge <EOS>
<BOS> the Axe, Brue, Cary, Parrett, Sheppey, Tone and Yeo <EOS>
<BOS> King Charles I, river tolls were levied on boats to pay for the maintenance of the bridge. <EOS>
<BOS> are a sparsely populated wetland area of central Somerset, between the Quantock and Mendip hills <EOS>
<BOS> marine clay levels along the coast, and the inland (often peat based) moors <EOS>
<BOS> the Polden Hills; land to the south is drained by the River Parrett while land to the north is drained by the River Axe and the River Brue <EOS>
<BOS> The total area of the Levels amounts to about 647.5 square kilometres (160,000 acres) <EOS>
<BOS> the Romans, and was restarted at various times: by the Anglo-Saxons <EOS>
<BOS> Minehead, Watchet, Burnham-on-Sea, Weston-super-Mare, Clevedon and Portishead <EOS>
<BOS> Bridgwater Bay, and is a National Nature Reserve <EOS>
<BOS> the coastline is high and dramatic where the plateau of Exmoor meets the sea, with high cliffs and waterfalls. <EOS>
<BOS> a temperate climate which is generally wetter and milder than the rest of the country <EOS>
<BOS> Annual sunshine rates are slightly less than the regional average of 1,600 hours <EOS>
<BOS> About 8–15 days of snowfall is typical <EOS>
<BOS> Average rainfall is around 700 mm (28 in) <EOS>
<BOS> Bridgwater was developed during the Industrial Revolution as the area's leading port <EOS>
<BOS> was a centre for the manufacture of bricks and clay roof tiles, and later cellophane, but those industries have now stopped <EOS>
<BOS> Bridgwater has developed as a distribution hub for companies such as Argos, Toolstation, Morrisons and Gerber Juice <EOS>
<BOS> AgustaWestland manufactures helicopters in Yeovil, and Normalair Garratt, builder of aircraft oxygen systems <EOS>
<BOS> Many towns have encouraged small-scale light industries, such as Crewkerne's Ariel Motor Company, one of the UK's smallest car manufacturers <EOS>
<BOS> defence equipment and technology. <EOS>
<BOS> A Royal Ordnance Factory, ROF Bridgwater was built at the start of the Second World War, between the villages of Puriton and Woolavington <EOS>
<BOS> Other high-technology companies include the optics company Gooch and Housego, at Ilminster <EOS>
<BOS> Norton Fitzwarren is the home of 40 Commando Royal Marines <EOS>
<BOS> The Royal Naval Air Station in Yeovilton, is one of Britain's two active Fleet Air Arm bases and is home to the Royal Navy's Lynx helicopters <EOS>
<BOS> Agriculture and food and drink production continue to be major industries in the county, employing over 15,000 people <EOS>
<BOS> Apple orchards were once plentiful, and Somerset is still a major producer of cider <EOS>
<BOS> Gerber Products Company in Bridgwater is the largest producer of fruit juices in Europe, producing brands such as "Sunny Delight" and "Ocean Spray <EOS>
<BOS> Cheddar cheese—some of which has the West Country Farmhouse Cheddar Protected Designation of Origin (PDO). <EOS>
<BOS> Traditional willow growing and weaving (such as basket weaving) is not as extensive as it used to be but is still carried out on the Somerset Levels <EOS>
<BOS> The willow was harvested using a traditional method of pollarding, where a tree would be cut back to the main stem <EOS>
<BOS> Largely due to the displacement of baskets with plastic bags and cardboard boxes, the industry has severely declined since the 1950s <EOS>
<BOS> The Somerset Levels is now the only area in the UK where basket willow is grown commercially. <EOS>
<BOS> Castle Cary and Frome grew around the medieval weaving industry <EOS>
<BOS> the work was transferred to lower-wage areas, such as China and Asia <EOS>
<BOS> Dr. Martens shoes were also made in Somerset, by the Northampton-based R. Griggs Group <EOS>
<BOS> supplying freestone and building stone <EOS>
<BOS> Ralph Allen promoted its use in the early 18th century, as did Hans Price in the 19th century <EOS>
<BOS> Blue Lias has been used locally as a building stone and as a raw material for lime mortar and Portland cement <EOS>
<BOS> the county has supplied aggregates. Foster Yeoman is Europe's large supplier of limestone aggregates <EOS>
<BOS> estimated in 2001 to support around 23,000 people <EOS>
<BOS> the coastal towns, part of the Exmoor National Park, the West Somerset Railway (a heritage railway), and the museum of the Fleet Air Arm at RNAS Yeovilton <EOS>
<BOS> mythical associations, including legends of a visit by the young Jesus of Nazareth and Joseph of Arimathea, with links to the Holy Grail, King Arthur <EOS>
<BOS> Glastonbury also gives its name to an annual open-air rock festival held in nearby Pilton <EOS>
<BOS> locally produced cheese, although there is now only one remaining cheese maker in the village of Cheddar <EOS>
<BOS> Hinkley Point C nuclear power station is a project to construct a 3,200 MW two reactor nuclear power station <EOS>
<BOS> Stop Hinkley, was formed to campaign for the closure of Hinkley Point B and oppose any expansion at the Hinkley Point site <EOS>
<BOS> opened an investigation to assess whether the project breaks state-aid rules <EOS>
<BOS> the European Commission has approved the project, with an overwhelming majority and only four commissioners voting against the decision. <EOS>
<BOS> Population growth is higher than the national average, with a 6.4% increase, in the Somerset County Council area, since 1991, and a 17% increase since 1981 <EOS>
<BOS> the unemployment rate is lower than the regional and national average. <EOS>
<BOS> is higher than the regional and national average <EOS>
<BOS> Somerset has a high indigenous British population, with 98.8% registering as white British and 92.4% of these as born in the United Kingdom <EOS>
<BOS> Chinese is the largest ethnic group <EOS>
<BOS> Over 25% of Somerset's population is concentrated in Taunton, Bridgwater and Yeovil <EOS>
<BOS> Over 9 million tourist nights are spent in Somerset each year <EOS>
<BOS> The ceremonial county of Somerset consists of a two-tier non-metropolitan county <EOS>
<BOS> The five districts of Somerset are West Somerset, South Somerset, Taunton Deane, Mendip, and Sedgemoor <EOS>
<BOS> North Somerset, and Bath & North East Somerset <EOS>
<BOS> Somerset is covered by the Avon and Somerset Constabulary, a police force which also covers Bristol and South Gloucestershire <EOS>
<BOS> The Devon and Somerset Fire and Rescue Service was formed in 2007 upon the merger of the Somerset Fire and Rescue Service with its neighbouring Devon service <EOS>

<BOS> inhabitation in the region of Utrecht, dating back to the Stone Age (app. 2200 BCE) <EOS>
<BOS> Claudius decided the empire should not expand north. <EOS>
<BOS> To consolidate the border the limes Germanicus defense line was constructed  along the main branch of the river Rhine <EOS>
<BOS> These fortresses were designed to house a cohort of about 500 Roman soldiers <EOS>
<BOS> Near the fort settlements would grow housing artisans, traders and soldiers' wives and children <EOS>
<BOS> Germanic tribes regularly invaded the Roman territories. <EOS>
<BOS> Around 275 the Romans could no longer maintain the northern border and Utrecht was abandoned <EOS>
<BOS> Little is known about the next period 270–650. <EOS>
<BOS> a church was built within the walls of the Roman fortress <EOS>
<BOS> In ongoing border conflicts with the Frisians this first church was destroyed. <EOS>
<BOS> English and Irish missionaries set out to convert the Frisians <EOS>
<BOS> The pope appointed their leader, Willibrordus, bishop of the Frisians <EOS>
<BOS> Frankish leader Charles Martel bestowed the fortress in Utrecht and the surrounding lands as the base of the bishops <EOS>
<BOS> After the fall of Dorestad around 850, Utrecht became one of the most important cities in the Netherlands <EOS>
<BOS> Utrecht as a centre of Christianity is illustrated by the election of the Utrecht-born Adriaan Florenszoon Boeyens as pope in 1522 <EOS>
<BOS> the Bishops of Utrecht came to exercise worldly power as prince-bishops <EOS>
<BOS> not only included the modern province of Utrecht (Nedersticht, 'lower Sticht'), but also extended to the northeast <EOS>
<BOS> The feudal conflict of the Middle Ages heavily affected Utrecht <EOS>
<BOS> the Counts of Holland and the Dukes of Guelders <EOS>
<BOS> The Veluwe region was seized by Guelders <EOS>
<BOS> The most dominant of these was the Cathedral of Saint Martin, inside the old Roman fortress <EOS>
<BOS> The construction of the present Gothic building was begun in 1254 after an earlier romanesque construction had been badly damaged by fire <EOS>
<BOS> the age of the great cathedrals had come to an end and declining finances prevented the ambitious project from being finished <EOS>
<BOS> Besides the cathedral there were four collegiate churches in Utrecht <EOS>
<BOS> the city housed St. Paul's Abbey, the 15th-century beguinage of St. Nicholas, and a 14th-century chapter house of the Teutonic Knights. <EOS>
<BOS> allowed Utrecht to become an important trade centre in the Northern Netherlands. <EOS>
<BOS> Henry V in 1122 <EOS>
<BOS> the bishop, who controlled many lands outside of the city, and the citizens of Utrecht was not always easy <EOS>
<BOS> The bishop, for example dammed the Kromme Rijn at Wijk bij Duurstede to protect his estates from flooding <EOS>
<BOS> In 1528 the bishop lost secular power over both Neder- and Oversticht – which included the city of Utrecht – to Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor <EOS>
<BOS> Charles V combined the Seventeen Provinces (the current Benelux and the northern parts of France) as a personal union <EOS>
<BOS> the prince-bishopric Utrecht, as the secular rule was now the lordship of Utrecht, with the religious power remaining with the bishop <EOS>
<BOS> In 1559 the bishopric of Utrecht was raised to archbishopric to make it the religious center of the Northern ecclesiastical province in the Seventeen provinces <EOS>
<BOS> Charles V was struggling to exert his power over the citizens of the city, who had struggled to gain a certain level of independence from the bishops <EOS>
<BOS> The heavily fortified castle Vredenburg was built to house a large garrison whose main task was to maintain control over the city <EOS>
<BOS> The castle would last less than 50 years before it was demolished in an uprising in the early stages of the Dutch Revolt <EOS>
<BOS> the northern seven provinces signed the Union of Utrecht, in which they decided to join forces against Spanish rule <EOS>
<BOS> The Union of Utrecht is seen as the beginning of the Dutch Republic <EOS>
<BOS> towards its dominant province Holland <EOS>
<BOS> Utrecht remained an atypical city in the new republic with about 40% Catholic in the mid-17th century, and even more among the elite groups <EOS>
<BOS> temporarily fell to the French invasion in 1672 (the Disaster Year); where the French invasion was only stopped west of Utrecht <EOS>
<BOS> the centre of Utrecht was struck by a tornado <EOS>
<BOS> The halt to building before construction of flying buttresses in the 15th century now proved to be the undoing of the central section of the cathedral <EOS>
<BOS> In 1713, Utrecht hosted one of the first international peace negotiations when the Treaty of Utrecht settled the War of the Spanish Succession <EOS>
<BOS> Utrecht became the centre of the non-Roman Old Catholic Churches in the world <EOS>
<BOS> the role of Utrecht as a fortified town had become obsolete <EOS>
<BOS> a railway connecting Utrecht to Amsterdam was opened <EOS>
<BOS> the Dutch government allowed the bishopric of Utrecht to be reinstated by Rome, and Utrecht became the centre of Dutch Catholicism <EOS>
<BOS> New middle class residential areas, such as Tuindorp and Oog in Al, were built <EOS>
<BOS> were developed following modernist ideas of the 1960s, in a brutalist style <EOS>
<BOS> the shopping mall Hoog Catharijne <EOS>
<BOS> In the early 21st century the whole area is being redeveloped <EOS>
<BOS> About 38% percent of its population either earns a minimum income or is dependent on social welfare <EOS>
<BOS> About 69% of the population is of Dutch ancestry <EOS>
<BOS> Kanaleneiland, Overvecht and Hoograven consist primarily of high-rise housing developments, and are known for relatively high poverty and crime rate <EOS>
<BOS> which makes concise definitions of its agglomeration difficult, and somewhat arbitrary. <EOS>
<BOS> smaller Utrecht agglomeration of continuously built up areas counts some 420,000 inhabitants and includes Nieuwegein, IJsselstein and Maarssen <EOS>
<BOS> The larger region, including slightly more remote towns such as Woerden and Amersfoort counts up to 820,000 inhabitants <EOS>
<BOS> Utrecht's cityscape is dominated by the Dom Tower, the tallest belfry in the Netherlands and originally part of the Cathedral of Saint Martin <EOS>
<BOS> An ongoing debate is over whether any building in or near the centre of town should surpass the Dom Tower in height (112 m) <EOS>
<BOS> the Nieuw Galgenwaard stadium (2007) <EOS>
<BOS> the old centre and the canal structure in the inner city <EOS>
<BOS> The inner city has largely retained its Medieval structure, and the moat ringing the old town is largely intact <EOS>
<BOS> Surrounding the medieval core there is a ring of late 19th- and early 20th-century neighbourhoods, with newer neighbourhoods positioned farther out <EOS>
<BOS> The eastern part of Utrecht remains fairly open <EOS>
<BOS> Utrecht Centraal is the main railway station of Utrecht <EOS>
<BOS> Utrecht Centraal is a station on the night service, providing 7 days a week an all night service <EOS>
<BOS> International InterCityExpress (ICE) services to Germany (and further) through Arnhem call at Utrecht Centraal <EOS>
<BOS> local trains to all areas surrounding Utrecht also depart from Utrecht Centraal; and service several smaller stations <EOS>
<BOS> The main local and regional bus station of Utrecht is located adjacent to Utrecht Centraal railway station, at the East and West entrances <EOS>
<BOS> large scale renovation and construction works at the railway station, the station's bus stops are changing frequently <EOS>
<BOS> Local buses in Utrecht are operated by Qbuzz – its services include a high-frequency service to the Uithof university district <EOS>
<BOS> The local bus fleet is one of Europe's cleanest, using only buses compliant with the Euro-VI standard as well as electric buses for inner city transport <EOS>
<BOS> Utrecht has an extensive network of cycle paths, making cycling safe and popular. 33% of journeys within the city are by bicycle <EOS>
<BOS> There are also barrow bikes, for carrying shopping or small children <EOS>
<BOS> in 2014 to build the world's largest bicycle parking station, near the Central Railway Station <EOS>
<BOS> well-connected to the Dutch road network. Two of the most important major roads serve the city of Utrecht: <EOS>
<BOS> A12 and A2 motorways connect Amsterdam, Arnhem, The Hague and Maastricht, as well as Belgium and Germany <EOS>
<BOS> increasing traffic and the ancient city plan, traffic congestion is a common phenomenon in and around Utrecht, causing elevated levels of air pollutants <EOS>
<BOS> The economy of Utrecht depends for a large part on the several large institutions located in the city <EOS>

<BOS> The competition is open to any club down to Level 10 of the English football league system <EOS>
<BOS> . All clubs in the top four levels (the Premier League and the three divisions of the Football League) are automatically eligible <EOS>

<BOS> There are 45 million Hispanophones who speak Spanish as a first or second language in the United States, <EOS>
<BOS> Roughly half of all American Spanish-speakers also speak English "very well," based on their self-assessment in the U.S. Census. <EOS>
<BOS> The Spanish language is the second most spoken language in the United States. <EOS>
<BOS> Spanish is the Romance language and the Indo-European language with the largest number of native speakers in the world. <EOS>
<BOS> six million Spanish language students. <EOS>
<BOS> The Spanish language has been present in what is now the United States since the 16th and 17th centuries <EOS>
<BOS> Spanish colonization in North America that would later become the states of Florida, Texas, Colorado, New Mexico, Arizona, Nevada, Utah, and California. <EOS>
<BOS> The Spanish explorers explored areas of 42 future U.S. states <EOS>
<BOS> western regions of the Louisiana Territory were under Spanish rule between 1763 to 1800, <EOS>
<BOS> after the French and Indian War, further extending the Spanish influence throughout modern-day United States of America. <EOS>
<BOS> Spanish arrived in the territory of the modern United States with Ponce de León in 1513. <EOS>
<BOS> Spanish was the language spoken by the first permanent European settlers in North America. <EOS>
<BOS> St. Augustine, Florida <EOS>
<BOS> The oldest city in all of the U.S. territory, as of 1898, is San Juan, capital of Puerto Rico <EOS>
<BOS> the Spaniards, by way of Juan Ponce de León, founded St. Augustine, Florida <EOS>
<BOS> In 1821, after Mexico's War of Independence from Spain, Texas was part of the United Mexican States as the state of Coahuila y Tejas <EOS>
<BOS> A large influx of Americans soon followed, originally with the approval of Mexico's president. In 1836 <EOS>
<BOS> Texans, fought a war of independence from the central government of Mexico <EOS>
<BOS> In 1846, the Republic dissolved when Texas entered the United States of America as a state. <EOS>
<BOS> Per the 1850 U.S. census, fewer than 16,000 Texans were of Mexican descent, and nearly all were Spanish-speaking people <EOS>
<BOS> After the Mexican War of Independence from Spain <EOS>
<BOS> California, Nevada, Arizona, Utah, western Colorado and southwestern Wyoming became part of the Mexican territory of Alta California <EOS>
<BOS> most of New Mexico, western Texas, southern Colorado, southwestern Kansas, and Oklahoma panhandle were part of the territory of Santa Fe de Nuevo México <EOS>
<BOS> The geographical isolation and unique political history of this territory <EOS>
<BOS> Through the force of sheer numbers, the English-speaking American settlers entering the Southwest established their language, culture, and law <EOS>
<BOS> United States never developed bilingualism as Canada did. <EOS>
<BOS> California constitutional convention of 1849 had eight Californio participants; the resulting state constitution was produced in English and Spanish, <EOS>
<BOS> the convention's English-speaking participants felt that the state's remaining minority of Spanish-speakers should simply learn English <EOS>
<BOS> the convention ultimately voted 46-39 to revise the earlier clause so that all official proceedings would henceforth be published only in English. <EOS>
<BOS> U.S. federal government strenuously tried to force Puerto Ricans to adopt English <EOS>
<BOS> making them use English as the primary language of instruction in their high schools. <EOS>
<BOS> It was completely unsuccessful, <EOS>
<BOS> Puerto Rico was able to maintain its Spanish language, culture, and identity because the relatively small, densely populated island <EOS>
<BOS> the territory was never hit with a massive influx of millions of English speakers like the vast territory acquired from Mexico 50 years earlier. <EOS>
<BOS> At over 5 million, Puerto Ricans are easily the 2nd largest Hispanic group. Of all major Hispanic groups <EOS>
<BOS> Puerto Ricans are the least likely to be proficient in Spanish <EOS>
<BOS> many Puerto Ricans have migrated to New York City, Orlando, Philadelphia, and other areas of the Eastern United States <EOS>
<BOS> increasing the Spanish-speaking populations and in some areas being the majority of the Hispanophone population, especially in Central Florida. In Hawaii <EOS>
<BOS> 7.0 per cent of the islands' people are either Hispanic or Hispanophone or both. <EOS>
<BOS> Immigration to the United States of Spanish-speaking Cubans began because of Cuba's political instability <EOS>
<BOS> The deposition of Fulgencio Batista's dictatorship and the ascension of Fidel Castro's government in 1959 increased Cuban immigration to the United States <EOS>
<BOS> , most settled in southern and central Florida, while other Cubans live in the Northeastern United States <EOS>
<BOS> most are fluent in Spanish <EOS>
<BOS> In the city of Miami today Spanish is the first language mostly due to Cuban immigration. <EOS>
<BOS> Spanish-speaking Nicaraguans <EOS>
<BOS> political instability during the end of the 1970s and the 1980s <EOS>
<BOS> Throughout the 1980s with the United States supported Contra War (or Contra-revolutionary war) which continued up until 1988 <EOS>
<BOS> The states of the United States where most Nicaraguans migrated to include Florida, California and Texas. <EOS>
<BOS> the economic collapse of the country many more Nicaraguans migrated to the United States amongst other countries. <EOS>
<BOS> The exodus of Salvadorans was a result of both economic and political problems. <EOS>
<BOS> The largest immigration wave occurred as a result of the Salvadoran Civil War in the 1980s <EOS>
<BOS> 20–30% of El Salvador's population emigrated. About 50%, or up to 500,000 of those who escaped headed to the United States, <EOS>
<BOS> United States, which was already home to over 10,000 Salvadorans, making Salvadorans Americans the fourth-largest Hispanic and Latino American group <EOS>
<BOS> Salvadorans Americans the fourth-largest Hispanic and Latino American group, after the Mexican-American majority, stateside Puerto Ricans, and Cubans. <EOS>
<BOS> civil wars engulfed several Central American countries in the 1980s <EOS>
<BOS> Salvadorans fled their country and came to the United States. Between 1980 and 1990 <EOS>
<BOS> the Salvadoran immigrant population in the United States increased nearly fivefold from 94,000 to 465,000. <EOS>
<BOS> the United States continued to grow in the 1990s and 2000s as a result of family reunification and new arrivals fleeing a series of natural disasters <EOS>
<BOS> By 2008, there were about 1.1 million Salvadoran immigrants in the United States. <EOS>
<BOS> Until the 20th century, there was no clear record of the number of Venezuelans who emigrated to the United States. <EOS>
<BOS> Between the 18th and early 19th centuries, there were many European immigrants who went to Venezuela <EOS>
<BOS> Many Venezuelans settled in the United States with hopes of receiving a better education, only to remain in there following graduation. <EOS>
<BOS> since the early 1980s, the reasons for Venezuelan emigration have changed to include hopes of earning a higher salary <EOS>
<BOS> In the 2000s, more Venezuelans opposing the economic and political policies of president Hugo Chávez migrated to the United States <EOS>
<BOS> mostly to Florida, but New York City and Houston are other destinations). The largest concentration of Venezuelans in the United States is in South Florida <EOS>
<BOS> New York, California, Texas (adding their existing Hispanic populations), New Jersey, Massachusetts and Maryland. <EOS>
<BOS> Some of the urban areas with a high Venezuelan community include Miami, New York City, Los Angeles, and Washington, D.C. <EOS>

<BOS> Some states, such as New Mexico, provide bilingual legislated notices and official documents <EOS>
<BOS> there was a trend that most Americans and American residents who are of Hispanic descent speak only English in the home. <EOS>
<BOS> United States has no de jure official language, English is the dominant language <EOS>
<BOS> The state (like its southwestern neighbors) has had close linguistic and cultural ties with Mexico <EOS>

<BOS> The area of the former Gadsden Purchase contained a majority of Spanish-speakers until the 1940s <EOS>
<BOS> the continuous arrival of Mexican settlers increases the number of Spanish-speakers. <EOS>
<BOS> the state has no official language. <EOS>
<BOS> New Mexico's laws are promulgated bilingually in Spanish and English. <EOS>
<BOS> Spanish has been spoken in the New Mexico-Colorado border and the contemporary U.S.–Mexico border since the 16th century <EOS>
<BOS> New Mexico is commonly thought to have Spanish as an official language alongside English because of its wide usage and legal promotion of Spanish in the state <EOS>
<BOS> Because of its relative isolation from other Spanish-speaking areas over most of its 400-year existence <EOS>
<BOS> , New Mexico Spanish, and in particular the Spanish of northern New Mexico and Colorado has retained many elements of 16th- and 17th-century Spanish <EOS>
<BOS> has developed its own vocabulary. In addition, it contains many words from Nahuatl, the language spoken by the ancient Aztecs of Mexico. <EOS>
<BOS> New Mexican Spanish also contains loan words from the Pueblo languages of the upper Rio Grande Valley, Mexican-Spanish words (mexicanismos) <EOS>
<BOS> borrowings from English. Grammatical changes include the loss of the second person verb form, changes in verb endings <EOS>
<BOS> In Texas, English is the state's de facto official language <EOS>
<BOS> , the continual influx of Spanish-speaking immigrants increased the import of Spanish in Texas. <EOS>
<BOS> . The Government of Texas, through Section 2054.116 of the Government Code, mandates that state agencies provide information on their websites in Spanish <EOS>
<BOS> websites in Spanish to assist residents who have limited English proficiency. <EOS>
<BOS> Spanish is currently the most widely taught non-English language <EOS>
<BOS> More than 1.4 million university students were enrolled in language courses <EOS>
<BOS> Spanish is the most widely taught language in American colleges and universities with 53 percent of the total number of people enrolled <EOS>
<BOS> French (14.4%), German (7.1%), Italian (4.5%), American Sign language (4.3%), Japanese (3.7%), and Chinese (2.4%) <EOS>
<BOS> totals remain relatively small in relation to the total U.S population. <EOS>

<BOS> on 14 February 2005 Arsenal were the first to name a completely foreign 16-man squad for a match <EOS>
<BOS> By 2009, under 40% of the players in the Premier League were English. <EOS>

<BOS> In response to concerns that clubs were increasingly passing over young English players in favour of foreign players <EOS>
<BOS> A non-EU player applying for the permit must have played for his country in at least 75 per cent of its competitive 'A' team matches <EOS>
<BOS> his country must have averaged at least 70th place in the official FIFA world rankings over the previous two years. <EOS>
<BOS> If a player does not meet those criteria, the club wishing to sign him may appeal. <EOS>

<BOS> Players may only be transferred during transfer windows that are set by the Football Association. <EOS>
<BOS> The two transfer windows run from the last day of the season to 31 August and from 31 December to 31 January. <EOS>
<BOS> Player registrations cannot be exchanged outside these windows except under specific licence from the FA, usually on an emergency basis. <EOS>
<BOS> As of the 2010–11 season, the Premier League introduced new rules mandating that each club must register a maximum 25-man squad of players aged over 21, <EOS>
<BOS> This was to enable the 'home grown' rule to be enacted, <EOS>

<BOS> The record transfer fee for a Premier League player has risen steadily over the lifetime of the competition. <EOS>

<BOS> Tottenham Hotspur selling Gareth Bale to Real Madrid for £85 million in 2013, <EOS>
<BOS> Manchester United's sale of Cristiano Ronaldo to Real Madrid for £80 million in 2009, <EOS>
<BOS> Liverpool selling Luis Suárez to Barcelona for £75 million in 2014. <EOS>
